Eh, MPS immediately sprang to mind when I saw the clue, number of letters, and had the ‚ÄòM‚Äô from the crossing‚Äîso you could say that the clue ‚Äúworked‚Äù insofar as it got me to the answer‚Äîbut I think the nit stands. I‚Äôd think the average American solver who doesn‚Äôt follow British or other non-US politics would tend to think of someone sitting in the House of Lords (if they ever were to think of one, to begin with) generically as a ‚ÄúBritish legislator‚Äù or ‚ÄúBritish lawmaker‚Äù; an American solver who does follow other countries‚Äô politics enough to have ‚ÄúMP‚Äù (not standing for ‚Äúmilitary police‚Äù or ‚Äúmagic/mana points‚Äù) as a familiar term in their head, by contrast, would tend to know that the term is, in practice, used only for members of the lower house, the Commons. This is, in fact, consistent across parliamentary systems: A Canadian or Australian ‚ÄúMP‚Äù is a member of the federal-level House of Commons or House of Representatives, respectively, not the Canadian or Australian Senate.

Sure, one could argue that someone who sits in the upper chamber in Westminster is, in a strictly literal sense, a ‚Äúmember of the UK‚Äôs parliament,‚Äù but a) that still doesn‚Äôt quite get to the specific abbreviation ‚ÄúMP,‚Äù and b) I would have to ask if you wouldn‚Äôt find something off about, say, [Bernie Sanders since 2007, for example] solving to CONGRESSMAN.

@Nick agreed. I would normally err on the side of taking these terms hyper-literally ‚Äî i.e., Lords are indeed members of parliament; and U.S. senators, as people who are part of Congress, are congresspeople. And it bothers me that this isn‚Äôt common usage, but the fact is that it isn‚Äôt. No one refers to Senators as congressmen, and Lords are very purposely referred to as *Lords* of Parliament to distinguish them from mere *Members.*

As I said, though, it‚Äôs established usage, but it‚Äôs ugly. The fact that House representatives go by ‚Äúcongressperson‚Äù but senators don‚Äôt is why some people think that a bill ‚Äúpassed by Congress‚Äù may still need the Senate‚Äôs approval, as if they were completely separate bodies. The general public‚Äôs handle on civic matters is tenuous enough as is, and imprecise nomenclature makes it worse. 

But that‚Äôs just the way things are. Groaning that Lords are technically members of the institution called Parliament, or that Senators are people who belong to Congress, is as futile as insisting that Quebecois are technically ‚ÄúLatin Americans‚Äù (a term coined by the French to contrast the broader Romance-speaking New World with the Anglo-Saxon colonies).

